;; Book of Narrative Games — Chapter 13: Multi-Character Scenes

(dialect :applies ("motoi" "sakura"))

(chapter
  :book                "Book of Narrative Games"
  :chapter-number      13
  :title               "Multi-Character Scenes"
  :dialect             "motoi"
  :audience            :kid
  :also-for            :adult
  :content-rating      :G
  :author-lane         "narrative-games-engineer-lane-2026-07-16"
  :training-eligible   #t
  :confidentiality     "public"
  :voice               "sakura-teaching + narrative-craft"
  :book-version        "1.0.0"
  :prose
"Two-character dialogue is easy. Three or more is theater. Who is
looking at whom? Who reacts when the third character speaks? Where
does the camera live? Who does the player interrupt?

This chapter is about scenes with three or more speaking characters.
The vocabulary is the same — `part/look-toward`, `part/turn`,
`world/camera-pan-to`, dialogue trees — but arranged as
choreography. We are directing a scene, not scripting a conversation.

The physics of ensemble scenes: every non-speaking character must be
DOING SOMETHING. Otherwise they read as furniture. A listener nods,
tilts, breathes. A listener who ignores becomes cold on purpose.
Nothing is neutral.

---

## 13.1 Setup — spawning three characters

```scheme
(define (three-character-scene)
  (scene/imagine)
  (surface/paper)

  ;; Spawn characters at their positions.
  (define mira    (make-character 'mira))
  (define father  (make-character 'father))
  (define niece   (make-character 'niece))

  (entity/set-pos! mira    120 200)
  (entity/set-pos! father  280 200)
  (entity/set-pos! niece   440 200)

  (entity/pose!    mira   'sitting)
  (entity/pose!    father 'sitting)
  (entity/pose!    niece  'sitting)

  ;; Each character's signature breath rate.
  (part/breathe mira    0.28)
  (part/breathe father  0.22)
  (part/breathe niece   0.38)

  ;; Camera on the group.
  (world/camera-snap! 280 200)
  (paint-text 20 40 \"Three chairs at a table. Nobody has started yet.\"))
```

Three characters, three positions, three signature breath rates.
The niece is the youngest, so she breathes fastest. Father is oldest,
slowest. Mira is between them.

The characters are placed left, center, right at the same y. Later
we might elevate some — the niece sits on a stool, the father on the
tallest chair. But start flat and add depth if needed.

The camera starts on the group — the center point between the three
of them. As the scene progresses, we will pan between speakers.

---

## 13.2 Turn-taking

The heart of ensemble choreography: when A speaks, B and C look at
A. When B responds, A and C look at B.

```scheme
;; Helper: everyone except the speaker looks at the speaker.
(define (turn-to-speaker speaker others)
  (for-each
    (lambda (listener)
      (part/look-toward listener (entity/x speaker) (entity/y speaker)))
    others))

;; The scene proceeds.
(define (dinner-conversation mira father niece)
  ;; Mira speaks.
  (turn-to-speaker mira (list father niece))
  (paint-text 20 100 \"MIRA: 'She's not coming.'\")

  (world/after 150
    (lambda ()
      ;; Father takes the beat.
      (part/lean father -4)                         ;; leans back
      (world/after 60
        (lambda ()
          (turn-to-speaker father (list mira niece))
          (paint-text 20 140 \"FATHER: 'No.'\")))))

  (world/after 400
    (lambda ()
      ;; Niece speaks after the silence.
      (turn-to-speaker niece (list mira father))
      (paint-text 20 180 \"NIECE: 'What do we do?'\")))

  (world/after 500
    (lambda ()
      ;; Mira answers — and looks at niece specifically.
      (turn-to-speaker mira (list father niece))
      (part/look-toward mira (entity/x niece) (entity/y niece))
      (paint-text 20 220 \"MIRA: 'We eat. That's all.'\"))))
```

The pattern: before each line, the speaker faces forward (or wherever
they should look), and the others turn to face the speaker. This one
helper — `turn-to-speaker` — carries the whole scene.

Notice line 4 in Mira's response: after the group turn, we
specifically point Mira at the niece. She is answering the niece's
question, not father's. Small target adjustments like this make the
scene feel real.

---

## 13.3 Reaction beats

When one character says something surprising, the others react. The
reactions carry more emotional weight than the line itself sometimes.

```scheme
;; A hard reveal.
(paint-text 20 100 \"MIRA: 'She said she is not coming back.'\")

(world/after 60
  (lambda ()
    ;; Father: freezes. Breath halts.
    (part/halt father)
    ;; Niece: leans in, curious more than sad.
    (part/lean niece 6)
    (part/tilt niece 8)))

;; Two seconds later, life comes back to father.
(world/after 200
  (lambda ()
    (part/breathe father 0.22)
    (part/turn father 'front)
    (paint-text 20 140 \"FATHER: 'When did she tell you.'\")))
```

Mira drops the news. Father freezes — halted breath. Niece leans in
(children process news physically). Two seconds of silence. Father
returns to breath, turns, asks a question.

Every character reacted. Nobody was furniture. The father's freeze
carries the emotional beat of the scene. The niece's lean is a
smaller register — she does not understand yet.

Design your reactions in advance. For every big line in the scene,
write down what each non-speaker does. This is the same discipline
theater directors call 'blocking.'

---

## 13.4 The player interrupts

In our dialogue trees so far the player has been ONE of the
speakers. In an ensemble scene, sometimes the player is present but
listening. Sometimes they want to break in.

```scheme
;; The player can press 'B' to break into the conversation.
(define (dinner-with-interrupt-option)
  ;; Set the scene as before.
  ;; ...

  (on-key
    (lambda (k)
      (when (eq? k 'b)
        (interrupt-happens)))))

(define (interrupt-happens)
  ;; The current speaker halts.
  (part/halt current-speaker)
  ;; They turn to the player.
  (part/turn current-speaker 'front)
  (part/lean current-speaker 4)      ;; leans forward to hear you
  ;; The others turn to the player too.
  (for-each
    (lambda (c)
      (part/look-toward c (input/mouse-x) (input/mouse-y)))
    (all-characters-except current-speaker))
  ;; Player gets to say their piece.
  (paint-text 20 300 \"You: [type your interruption]\")
  (input/text-buffer 20 340
    :on-submit
    (lambda (text)
      (paint-text 20 380 (string-append \"You said: '\" text \"'\"))
      ;; The characters react.
      (world/after 60
        (lambda () (react-to-interruption text))))))
```

The player presses B. The current speaker halts mid-sentence, turns
to the player, leans forward. Everyone else turns to look at the
player. The player types their interruption. When they submit,
characters react.

`react-to-interruption` can be as simple as everyone nodding, or as
complex as a semantic classification of the interruption content that
triggers different reactions. Chapter 12 gives you the tools; use
what feels right for your scene.

Not every scene needs to allow interruption. In fact most should not
— an ensemble scene that keeps getting derailed by player
interruptions never builds momentum. Reserve interruption for scenes
where the player's voice matters.

---

## 13.5 The camera in ensemble scenes

Camera choices in three-way scenes are trickier than in two-way. Some
options:

**Wide the whole time.** Camera stays on the group; the audience
sees all three faces. Works for scenes where the group dynamic is
the point.

**Cut between close-ups.** Every line gets its own close-up. Feels
cinematic but expensive — twelve cuts in a two-minute scene, and
the player's brain gets tired.

**Pan between speakers.** Camera drifts to whoever speaks. Works
when there are only two active speakers and one silent observer.
Great for tense confrontations where the silent observer's face
holds the emotional weight.

**Follow the focus character.** Pick ONE character whose face is the
scene's emotional throughline. Camera stays on them, watching them
react to what others say. Works for scenes about ONE person even
though many are talking.

Here is the follow-the-focus variant.

```scheme
;; The scene is 'about' the niece — how she absorbs what the adults say.
;; The camera stays on her.
(define (niece-focus-scene)
  (world/camera-follow! niece :ease 0.1)

  ;; Adults have their conversation.
  (mira-says \"She's not coming.\")
  (father-says \"No.\")
  (mira-says \"We eat. That's all.\")

  ;; During all of this, the niece's face is what we see.
  ;; Every time an adult speaks, we watch how she reacts.
  )
```

The audience never sees father's face. Never sees Mira's face. They
see the niece hearing her family talk about the loss. That is a very
different scene from the wide version — even though the dialogue is
identical.

Choosing the camera is choosing whose experience the scene is about.

---

## 13.6 A worked scene: the three-way negotiation

Two shopkeepers and a customer. The customer wants to trade a piece
from one shop as partial payment on a piece from the other. Neither
shopkeeper wants to say yes first.

```scheme
(define (three-way-negotiation)
  (scene/imagine)
  (surface/paper)

  ;; Three positions.
  (define anna    (make-character 'anna))     ;; shopkeeper 1
  (define bea     (make-character 'bea))      ;; shopkeeper 2
  (define customer (make-character 'customer)) ;; the player character

  (entity/set-pos! anna    100 200)
  (entity/set-pos! bea     500 200)
  (entity/set-pos! customer 300 300)

  (part/breathe anna 0.30)
  (part/breathe bea  0.25)
  (part/breathe customer 0.45)

  (world/camera-snap! 300 220)

  ;; Customer opens.
  (turn-to-speaker customer (list anna bea))
  (paint-text 20 40
    \"YOU: 'I'd take Bea's chair if I could put Anna's lamp against it.'\")

  ;; Anna and Bea look at each other, not at the customer.
  (world/after 120
    (lambda ()
      (part/look-toward anna (entity/x bea) (entity/y bea))
      (part/look-toward bea (entity/x anna) (entity/y anna))))

  ;; Long silence. Both are calculating.
  (world/after 240
    (lambda ()
      (paint-text 20 80 \"[Anna and Bea study each other for a long moment.]\")))

  ;; Anna speaks first.
  (world/after 400
    (lambda ()
      (turn-to-speaker anna (list bea customer))
      (part/lean anna 4)
      (paint-text 20 120 \"ANNA: 'The lamp is worth two-thirty.'\")))

  ;; Bea considers.
  (world/after 550
    (lambda ()
      (part/tilt bea 10)              ;; head tilt: considering
      (part/sway bea 3)))              ;; small sway

  (world/after 700
    (lambda ()
      (turn-to-speaker bea (list anna customer))
      (paint-text 20 160 \"BEA: 'The chair is four hundred. I'd take one-eighty\")
      (paint-text 20 185 \"in cash and the lamp — but Anna, you're too generous.'\")))

  ;; Camera cuts to Anna as she considers.
  (world/after 900
    (lambda ()
      (cine/shot 'close-up anna 90)
      (part/expression anna 'thinking)))

  ;; Anna's decision.
  (world/after 1050
    (lambda ()
      (part/nod anna)
      (paint-text 20 220 \"ANNA: 'Two-ten. Split the difference.'\")))

  ;; Bea nods, deal is done.
  (world/after 1200
    (lambda ()
      (cine/shot 'wide 'group 60)
      (part/nod bea)
      (paint-text 20 260 \"BEA: 'Done. Take the chair. Bring the lamp Tuesday.'\")))

  ;; Customer gets the last beat.
  (world/after 1350
    (lambda ()
      (turn-to-speaker customer (list anna bea))
      (paint-text 20 300 \"YOU: 'Tuesday. Thank you both.'\"))))
```

Twenty-two seconds. Three characters. The audience sees the whole
negotiation in body language — Anna and Bea looking at each other
without speaking, the long calculation, the small tilts and sways.
The dialogue is spare. The choreography carries the scene.

The reader who has been working through this book will now spot every
technique: turn-to-speaker helper, signature breath rates, camera
cuts at emotional beats, `part/tilt` and `part/sway` as thinking
markers, `close-up` when a character considers alone, `wide` when the
group closes a deal.

You can build this scene. You built the tools for it in every
previous chapter.

---

## 13.7 Common desktop tasks — a three-person shop chat

A customer, the shopkeeper, and a specialist. The customer has a
question the shopkeeper doesn't know the answer to; she pings the
specialist.

```scheme
(define-card 'three-person-consult
  :init
  (lambda ()
    (scene/imagine)
    (surface/paper)

    (define shopkeeper (make-character 'shopkeeper))
    (define specialist (make-character 'specialist))
    (define customer   (make-character 'customer))

    (entity/set-pos! shopkeeper 200 200)
    (entity/set-pos! specialist 400 200)
    (entity/set-pos! customer   300 320)

    (part/breathe shopkeeper 0.30)
    (part/breathe specialist 0.28)
    (part/breathe customer   0.40)

    ;; Customer asks a question.
    (turn-to-speaker customer (list shopkeeper specialist))
    (paint-text 20 40
      \"CUSTOMER: 'Would this work on cast iron?'\")

    ;; Shopkeeper looks at specialist.
    (world/after 120
      (lambda ()
        (part/look-toward shopkeeper (entity/x specialist) (entity/y specialist))
        (part/shrug shopkeeper)))

    ;; Specialist steps in.
    (world/after 240
      (lambda ()
        (turn-to-speaker specialist (list shopkeeper customer))
        (part/nod specialist)
        (paint-text 20 100
          \"SPECIALIST: 'On cast iron, yes, if it's already seasoned.'\")))

    ;; Shopkeeper thanks specialist.
    (world/after 400
      (lambda ()
        (turn-to-speaker shopkeeper (list specialist))
        (part/nod shopkeeper)
        (paint-text 20 140 \"SHOPKEEPER: 'Thank you.'\")))

    ;; Customer takes the answer.
    (world/after 500
      (lambda ()
        (turn-to-speaker customer (list shopkeeper specialist))
        (paint-text 20 180 \"CUSTOMER: 'Great — I'll take it.'\")))))
```

Three characters. Fifteen seconds. The shopkeeper's shrug when asked
is honest — she didn't know. The specialist stepped in. The customer
got the answer she needed. Everyone acted like a real person.

The operator who ships a cart like this is signaling to customers
that her shop is a place where you can ASK — because if the
shopkeeper doesn't know, someone will. That is the difference between
a shop and a store.

---

## 13.8 Routing patterns

**Never more than four active speakers.** Three is comfortable. Four
is manageable. Five gets confusing — the audience loses track of
who is who. If you need a bigger group, have some characters be
non-speaking presence.

**Assign a focus character per beat.** Every moment in the scene
should have ONE character whose face the audience is watching.
Switch focus at emotional beats. Never split attention.

**Let silence carry beats.** In a two-person scene, silence is
awkward. In a three-person scene, silence is dense — everyone is
reacting to what was just said. Trust silence more in ensemble
scenes than you would in two-person.

---

## 13.9 Closing

Ensemble scenes are the hardest thing in narrative games. They are
also the moments players remember. The dinner where nobody spoke
about the thing everyone was thinking about. The negotiation where
two shopkeepers stared each other down. The consult where the
shopkeeper shrugged and asked for help.

Every technique you have — breath, turn, tilt, camera cut, motif —
comes together here. Practice with small scenes. Three people, six
lines. Then scale up.

Chapter 14 is a strange one. Playable poetry. Games that are not
games — experiences that happen to run on the runtime. Some of the
most memorable things you can make.")
